  "prompt": "How would I find the necessary number of turns on a transformer primary if the secondary voltage required is 120 V at 60 Hz?",
  "response": "To find the number of turns on a transformer primary, you'll need some additional information. Here's the basic approach:\n\n1. Use the transformer turn ratio equation:\nNp/Ns = Vp/Vs\n\nWhere:\nNp = Number of primary turns\nNs = Number of secondary turns\nVp = Primary voltage\nVs = Secondary voltage\n\n2. You'll also need to know the primary voltage (input voltage)\n\nFor example:\n- If primary voltage is 240V and secondary needs to be 120V\n- 240V/120V = 2/1 turn ratio\n- If primary has 200 turns, secondary would have 100 turns\n\nKey requirements:\n- Know the input (primary) voltage\n- Understand the desired secondary voltage\n- Desired output current/power rating\n\nWithout knowing the specific primary voltage, it's impossible to precisely calculate the number of primary turns. The calculation depends on the input voltage and desired turn ratio.\n\nWould you like to provide more details about the specific transformer design and input voltage?",
